recordings.rmk: Same individual as XC595757 (recorded three days earlier, identified by unique call).

Natural vocalizations (although likely provoked by my presence). Two cuts from the same adult. The calls degrade into a "chup" I have not previously heard from this species, closer to the typical Lincoln's Sparrow calls than anything I have ever heard from LCSP. The flight calls in the second cut also nicely display the plasticity of these calls when not normalized as they likely are during nocturnal migration.

recordings.file-name: XC594756-LCSP (Juv) - Flight Call, Call - Prairie Green 2020-10-09 07_46 Combined.mp3
recordings.rmk:
Natural vocalizations (three cuts) from a juvenile.

The first cut contains only two "flight" calls given from the ground; the minute-long silence between the calls is preserved (the second flight call is at the 1:00 mark). There is some wind interference in the second cut.

Like many LeConte's Sparrows I've encountered, this one proved to be quite curious, coming within a few feet to get a closer look at the odd creature invading its habitat.
